		<td valign="top">
  			<table width="100%" height="100%" border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
  				<tr>
  					<td align=center valign="top" width=100%><br>
  						<!--#beginContent#-->
  						<table align='center' cellpadding=5 width='85%'>  <tr><td class='spti2' width='100%'>PLAYER STRATEGY - SHAMAN</td></tr>  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><font class='dbti'>BARBARIANS GUIDE TO HUNTING THE 'LIL MAMMOTHS</font> - <small>Mad John, Bristlebane</td></tr>
  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'>Once you make it to level 8 Everfrost becomes a LOT safer. You can now go to the Tundra to hunt Snow Leopards and Orc Troopers. Find Bandl (just south of Snowflake, and if you made it to lvl 8 you should know where that is) and go to the ledge that is directly in front of him. You will see what looks like a dried up riverbed in front of you. It is in that aria that you should hunt, running to Bandl if you hit any trouble. You should get to nine fairly fast, as there are a lot of kitties for you to kill, and once at nine the real fun begins.
<BR>
<BR>
Once there go back to town and get your spells-- if you don't have enough for them then spend some time slaughtering the lvl 2 bears, continue until you find a HQ bear pelt and sell it for 30pp. Make absolutely sure that you get SOW and Tainted Breath (from Bearjumper, his loc is listed in the spell info on this site), you will need them. 
<BR>
<BR>
Go back then to Bandl's ledge and start killing everything from blue to white. You should be able to take on Mammoth Calf's at this point. A lot of people will want to group with you (as a lot will be in the aria), but do not do it. You do not need a group to survive here, and if you join one (even if only with one other person in it) leveling will be three to four times as slow at least.
<BR>
<BR>
If you find yourself having trouble killing the white calf's, get some better equipment. Banded armor goes for about 1pp per AC, so a few hours spent killing lvl 2 bears will probably get you a full set. High levels at the Ice Giants (IG) will also often call for a banker-- what they are asking is for someone to come by and exchange pp for their gold, silver, and copper. If you have enough pp to cover it (usually 20pp minimum) you can help them out, and they will often give you between 10 and 40pp for your trouble. Too much gold and copper can weigh you down, however, and that's just one more reason to get yourself bound in Halas bank.
<BR>
<BR>
If you can handle whites pretty easy in plain combat (they don't usually take you down more than two to three bulbs), then it would be advisable for you to start going after yellow calf's as well. Now, I've seen groups of fighters balk at the idea of killing a yellow one, but don't worry-- you can do it. This is how: you cast SOW on yourself and keep track of how long you have before it drops. Make sure you are at full health and mana (or within 1 bulb of full mana) before combat (as well as making sure that you still have time left on your SOW). Stand pretty far away from the yellow calf and blast him with Tainted Breath. As you cast turn, it will interrupt the spell if you move, but turning should be fine, and as the timer disappears from the top left corner of your screen start running. Wait before the sound of Mammoth steps behind you are fairly faint and cast Sicken on the Calf. Run from it until you get a message telling you that the Tainted Breath spell has worn off. When that happens cast it again. It also might be a good idea to turn around at that point and run the other direction to avoid getting too far away from the guards, as soon as you have room to do so without the mammoth getting a free shot or two in on the way. Do this until you run out of mana, and as you cast the last TB spell turn and start fighting. By then the Calf should be down to about half life (even counting all the times they resist your TB) and you should be able to take them out with about the same HP loss as you get with white calf's.
<BR>
<BR>
You will run into a few problems while doing this. One, kitties and orcs will develop fetishes for attacking you while you're running. You look for 10 minutes and never find one, but the second you get a calf two or three will be biting at your heels. I don't know exactly how it works, but it does seem to be a fundamental law. Sometimes they will wait until the calf is pretty well blasted, and if you think that you can take the calf, even with the kitty clawing at you, feel free to try. Just to remember to run when you hit 2 bulbs if there is much of a chance of loosing, because if you don't your SOW won't help you in the least bit. Remember: if you see something in your path that might attack, steer around it!
<BR>
<BR>
Secondly, sometimes Calf production will slow down to the point where you will start wondering if you got a patch within the last few days. Goblin Scouts and Wooly Spiders are place holders for the Calfves, and if there aren't enough (and there rarely are) just slaughter a few of these. Wait about 2 minutes and you will be thrilled to witness the miracle of birth. Because there are place holders, however, you never know if you will get a brood of Calves or a brood of Scouts, and they do tend to spawn in groups. This will tempt you to kill as many as you can in hopes of getting a Calf to spawn, but this is dangerous-- if you get too close to one Calf while aggroing another you will have two Calves to worry about rather than one. And if you kill a lot of scouts in a short amount of time, you will probably get a lot of Calf spawn in a short amount of time. And although some have a taste for gang-bangs, you will be sore afterwards at least-- so try to avoid it.
<BR>
<BR>
This should get you to lvl 14 easy, and even to 15 or 16 if you're patient. Once you get the spells at 14, however, the entire play strategy changes-- and such is another matter completely.
<BR>
<BR>
If you need further help, or whatever, look me up in game.</td></tr>
  <tr><td class='db'>&nbsp;</td></tr>
